{"questionId":"22225","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The equation&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mi>p</mi><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>p</mi><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi></math>&nbsp;has two real, distinct roots.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Consider the case when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>. The roots of the equation can be expressed in&nbsp;the form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>±</mo><msqrt><mn>13</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math>, where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">ℤ</mi></math>. Find the value of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>p</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mn>12</mn><msup><mi>x</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p>\n<p>valid attempt to use&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>±</mo><msqrt><msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>a</mi><mi>c</mi></msqrt></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>a</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>±</mo><msqrt><mn>208</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>24</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>±</mo><msqrt><mn>13</mn></msqrt></mrow><mn>6</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><